    The crash occurs because the program tries to access memory beyond the      
    bounds of the arrays buffer due to a critical flaw in the initialization    
    loop in more_arrays().                                                      
                                                                                
    Here's the root cause analysis:                                             
                                                                                
     1 The function more_arrays() is called to dynamically increase the size    
       of the arrays array (used for storing array variables by name). It       
       works by:                                                                
        • Saving the old size in old_count = a_count                            
        • Allocating new space: a_count += STORE_INCR and arrays =              
          (bc_var_array **) bc_malloc(a_count * sizeof(bc_var_array *))         
        • Copying existing elements: for (indx = 1; indx < old_count; indx++)   
          arrays[indx] = old_ary[indx];                                         
        • Initializing new elements: for (; indx < v_count; indx++)             
          arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                  
     2 The problem lies in the final loop: for (; indx < v_count; indx++)       
       arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                     
     3 v_count represents the current number of variables (not arrays), and in  
       the test case, it's 741,488,172 — a huge number.                         
     4 But a_count is only 32, meaning the arrays buffer has space for only 32  
       elements.                                                                
     5 The loop attempts to write to arrays[32], arrays[33], ... all the way    
       to arrays[741,488,172], which is millions of elements beyond the         
       allocated buffer (only 32 elements were allocated).                      
     6 This causes a heap buffer overflow, corrupting heap metadata and memory  
       used by other parts of the program.                                      
     7 Later, when find_id() tries to access tree->id via strcmp() on the       
       corrupted heap, it hits invalid memory, causing the EXC_BAD_ACCESS       
       crash at address 0x58646f586288586 (which is a heap address that got     
       corrupted).                                                              
                                                                                
    The root cause is that the loop should use a_count (array count) as the     
    upper bound for initialization, not v_count (variable count). The loop is   
    initialized as for (; indx < v_count; indx++) — but indx starts from        
    old_count, and the condition should be indx < a_count, not v_count.         
                                                                                
    This is a classic off-by-one error where a variable with an unrelated       
    purpose (v_count) is incorrectly used as the loop limit.                    
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    ROOT CAUSE: bc/storage.c at line 176 in more_arrays(): The loop for (;      
    indx < v_count; indx++) uses v_count (variable count) as the upper bound    
    for initializing arrays, but v_count can be much larger than a_count        
    (array count). This causes an out-of-bounds write to the arrays buffer,     
    corrupting heap memory and resulting in a crash during later access.        
                                                                                
    LOCAL FIX: Replace v_count with a_count in the loop condition.              
                                                                                
                                                                                
     for (; indx < a_count; indx++)                                             
         arrays[indx] = NULL;                                                   
                                                                                
                                                                                
    GLOBAL FIX: Refactor more_arrays() to use a proper size increment           
    mechanism that ensures array size grows predictably and safely. Introduce   
    a constant STORE_INCR (if not already defined) and ensure array             
    initialization only goes up to a_count, not any unrelated variable count.   
    Additionally, use type safety and bounds-checking abstractions (e.g.        
    size_t for sizes, range checks) to prevent similar issues.                  
                                                                                
    Even better: Use a struct with size_t for array counts and include          
    invariant checks at every resize.                                           
                                                                                
